---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---
<Base title="What is llms.txt? The Complete Guide (2025)" description="The definitive guide to llms.txt — the AI README standard for websites. Spec explainer, best practices, real examples from Anthropic, Cloudflare, Stripe, and more.">
  <article class="learn-page">
    <div class="container content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/learn/llms-txt">Learn</a> / <span>llms.txt</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>What is llms.txt? The Complete Guide</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        <strong>llms.txt</strong> is a proposed standard (created by <a href="https://jeremy.fast.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Jeremy Howard</a>, Sept 2024) that gives AI language models
        structured information about your website. Think of it as a README for AI — it tells models what your site does,
        what's important, and where to find key content.
      </p>

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2 class="toc-title">On this page</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#why">Why llms.txt matters</a></li>
          <li><a href="#format">The format (full spec)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#examples">Real-world examples</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-practices">Best practices</a></li>
          <li><a href="#llms-full">llms.txt vs llms-full.txt</a></li>
          <li><a href="#adoption">Who's using it</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">Comparison with other files</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
          <li><a href="#implementation">Implementation checklist</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>

      <section id="why">
        <h2>Why llms.txt matters</h2>
        <p>
          AI models are already reading your website. ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, Gemini, and dozens of others
          browse the web every day. Without llms.txt, they have to guess what your site is about by crawling pages,
          parsing HTML, and hoping the important stuff is near the top.
        </p>
        <p>That's a bad bet. Here's what llms.txt actually solves:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Control the narrative.</strong> You decide what AI knows about you. Your tagline, your key pages, your documentation structure. Not whatever Google's snippet picked up 3 months ago.</li>
          <li><strong>Better AI search results.</strong> When someone asks ChatGPT or Perplexity about your product, the answer comes from your llms.txt, not a random blog post from 2019.</li>
          <li><strong>Structured context for RAG.</strong> Applications that use Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) can ingest your llms.txt as a primary source, getting the site map and key URLs in one request instead of crawling hundreds of pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Save AI tokens.</strong> A well-structured llms.txt gives models the information they need in ~2KB instead of forcing them to process megabytes of HTML.</li>
          <li><strong>Future-proof SEO.</strong> As AI-powered search (GEO: Generative Engine Optimization) grows, having structured AI-readable content becomes as important as traditional SEO.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="format">
        <h2>The format (full spec)</h2>
        <p>llms.txt is a simple Markdown-like text file placed at <code>/llms.txt</code> on your domain root. It follows a strict structure:</p>
        <pre><code># Your Site Name

> A brief description of what your site does.

## Docs

- [Getting Started](https://example.com/docs/getting-started): Quick start guide
- [API Reference](https://example.com/docs/api): Full API documentation
- [Authentication](https://example.com/docs/auth): How auth works

## Blog

- [Latest Release](https://example.com/blog/v2): What's new in v2

## Optional

- [Pricing](https://example.com/pricing): Plans and billing
- [Changelog](https://example.com/changelog): Version history</code></pre>

        <h3>Structure rules</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Title (required):</strong> First line must be <code># Your Site Name</code>. This is how AI models will refer to your product.</li>
          <li><strong>Description (recommended):</strong> A blockquote (<code>&gt;</code>) or paragraph immediately after the title. Keep it under 200 characters. This is your elevator pitch to AI.</li>
          <li><strong>Sections (recommended):</strong> Use <code>## Section Name</code> headings to organize links. Common sections: Docs, API, Blog, Guides, Legal.</li>
          <li><strong>Links (recommended):</strong> Markdown links with descriptions: <code>- [Title](URL): Description</code>. The colon-separated description is important, it tells the AI what each page contains without fetching it.</li>
          <li><strong>Optional section:</strong> Links under <code>## Optional</code> are lower-priority. AI models may skip these when context is limited.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Content type</h3>
        <p>
          Serve your llms.txt as <code>text/plain</code> or <code>text/markdown</code>. Both work. Most web servers
          default to <code>text/plain</code> for <code>.txt</code> files, which is fine.
        </p>

        <h3>Size guidelines</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Size</th><th>Recommendation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Under 2KB</td><td>Ideal for most sites</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2-10KB</td><td>Good for large documentation sites</td></tr>
            <tr><td>10-50KB</td><td>Acceptable, but consider using llms-full.txt for the extended version</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Over 50KB</td><td>Too large. AI models will truncate. Split into llms.txt (summary) + llms-full.txt (complete)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section id="examples">
        <h2>Real-world examples</h2>
        <p>Here's how major companies structure their llms.txt files:</p>

        <h3>Anthropic (docs.anthropic.com)</h3>
        <pre><code># Anthropic

> Anthropic is an AI safety company that builds reliable, interpretable, and steerable AI systems.

## Docs

- [API Reference](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/api): Complete API documentation
- [User Guides](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs): Guides for using Claude
- [Prompt Engineering](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering): Best practices for prompts</code></pre>

        <h3>A SaaS product</h3>
        <pre><code># Acme Analytics

> Real-time product analytics for SaaS teams. Track events, build funnels, run A/B tests.

## Docs

- [Getting Started](https://acme.com/docs/quickstart): Install the SDK and send your first event in 5 minutes
- [JavaScript SDK](https://acme.com/docs/sdk/javascript): Browser and Node.js integration
- [REST API](https://acme.com/docs/api): Server-side event ingestion

## Guides

- [Funnel Analysis](https://acme.com/docs/guides/funnels): Build and optimize conversion funnels
- [Cohort Retention](https://acme.com/docs/guides/retention): Track user retention over time

## Optional

- [Pricing](https://acme.com/pricing): Free tier available, scales with events
- [Status](https://status.acme.com): System uptime and incident history</code></pre>

        <h3>A personal blog / portfolio</h3>
        <pre><code># Jane Doe

> Software engineer writing about distributed systems, Rust, and developer tools.

## Writing

- [Building a Database from Scratch](https://jane.dev/posts/building-a-database): Series on implementing a key-value store in Rust
- [Why I Left Big Tech](https://jane.dev/posts/leaving-big-tech): Reflections on indie development

## Projects

- [kvstore](https://github.com/jane/kvstore): Embedded key-value database in Rust
- [dotfiles](https://github.com/jane/dotfiles): My development environment setup</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section id="best-practices">
        <h2>Best practices</h2>
        <div class="practices-grid">
          <div class="practice do">
            <h4>Do</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Keep it concise, under 50KB. AI models have context limits.</li>
              <li>Lead with your most important pages (docs, pricing, getting started).</li>
              <li>Use descriptive link text, not "click here" or raw URLs.</li>
              <li>Add a colon-separated description after each link.</li>
              <li>Serve as <code>text/plain</code> or <code>text/markdown</code> content type.</li>
              <li>Update when you ship major changes to your site structure.</li>
              <li>Include your product's value proposition in the description.</li>
              <li>Group links logically by section (Docs, Blog, Legal, etc.).</li>
              <li>Test your llms.txt with our <a href="/tools/playground">Playground</a> validator.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="practice dont">
            <h4>Don't</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Don't include every page on your site. Pick the 10-30 most important.</li>
              <li>Don't use HTML. It's a plain text/markdown file.</li>
              <li>Don't duplicate your sitemap.xml. llms.txt is curated, sitemap is comprehensive.</li>
              <li>Don't include login-required pages unless the content is genuinely useful to AI.</li>
              <li>Don't use relative URLs. Always use absolute URLs with the full domain.</li>
              <li>Don't add marketing fluff. AI models don't need "Award-winning platform" language.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="llms-full">
        <h2>llms.txt vs llms-full.txt</h2>
        <p>
          The spec defines two files:
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Size</th><th>Content</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>/llms.txt</code></td>
              <td>Summary for quick context</td>
              <td>Under 10KB</td>
              <td>Title, description, key links with descriptions</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>/llms-full.txt</code></td>
              <td>Complete documentation dump</td>
              <td>Up to a few MB</td>
              <td>Full text of all key documentation pages, concatenated</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          <strong>When to use llms-full.txt:</strong> If your product has extensive documentation (API references,
          tutorials, guides), llms-full.txt lets AI models ingest everything in one request. This is especially
          useful for code generation tools like Cursor, Copilot, and Claude that need deep technical context.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Most sites only need llms.txt.</strong> If you're a blog, a SaaS landing page, or a small site,
          the summary file is enough. Only add llms-full.txt if you have substantial documentation that AI tools
          would benefit from having in full.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="adoption">
        <h2>Who's using llms.txt</h2>
        <p>
          Adoption is growing fast. As of early 2025, hundreds of sites have adopted llms.txt,
          including major tech companies, frameworks, and open source projects:
        </p>
        <div class="adoption-grid">
          <div class="adoption-category">
            <h4>AI Companies</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Anthropic (docs.anthropic.com)</li>
              <li>Perplexity (docs.perplexity.ai)</li>
              <li>Cursor (cursor.com)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="adoption-category">
            <h4>Developer Tools</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Cloudflare (developers.cloudflare.com)</li>
              <li>Stripe (docs.stripe.com)</li>
              <li>Vercel (vercel.com)</li>
              <li>Supabase (supabase.com)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="adoption-category">
            <h4>Frameworks & Libraries</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>FastAPI (fastapi.tiangolo.com)</li>
              <li>Pydantic (docs.pydantic.dev)</li>
              <li>Astro (astro.build)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="hint">
          Want to check if a site has llms.txt? <a href="/">Scan it with our tool</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="comparison">
        <h2>How it relates to other files</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Audience</th><th>Analogy</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>robots.txt</code></td><td>Control which bots can crawl</td><td>All crawlers</td><td>The lock on your door</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>llms.txt</code></td><td>Tell AI what your site is about</td><td>AI language models</td><td>The welcome packet</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>ai.txt</code></td><td>AI usage policy & permissions</td><td>AI companies</td><td>The terms of the lease</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sitemap.xml</code></td><td>List all pages for indexing</td><td>Search engines & crawlers</td><td>The floor plan</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          These files work together. <code>robots.txt</code> controls access, <code>sitemap.xml</code> lists all pages,
          <code>llms.txt</code> curates the important ones for AI, and <code>ai.txt</code> sets the legal terms.
          A complete AI strategy uses all four.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="faq">
        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is llms.txt an official web standard?</h3>
          <p>
            Not yet. It's a proposal by Jeremy Howard (creator of fast.ai, former Kaggle president) published in September 2024.
            It doesn't have W3C or IETF backing, but adoption has been rapid because the format is simple and the need is real.
            It follows the same pattern as robots.txt, which was also a community convention before being formally standardized.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Do AI models actually read llms.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes. Browsing-enabled models (ChatGPT with browsing, Claude with web access, Perplexity)
            check for llms.txt when they visit a site. RAG-based applications and AI code editors
            (Cursor, Windsurf) also use it to load context about libraries and frameworks.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Will llms.txt hurt my SEO?</h3>
          <p>
            No. llms.txt is a separate file that doesn't affect how Google or Bing index your pages.
            It's additive: it gives AI models an extra signal on top of your existing SEO.
            In fact, better AI representation can drive more traffic as AI-powered search grows.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How often should I update my llms.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            Whenever your site structure changes significantly. New product launch, major docs rewrite,
            new blog series. You don't need to update it for every blog post. Think of it like updating
            your README, not your changelog.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What if I don't want AI to read my site?</h3>
          <p>
            Don't create an llms.txt. Use <a href="/learn/robots-txt">robots.txt</a> to block AI crawlers,
            and <a href="/learn/ai-txt">ai.txt</a> to declare your policy. llms.txt is opt-in, there's no
            penalty for not having one beyond missing out on better AI representation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can I use llms.txt on a subdomain?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes. Place it at the root of each subdomain: <code>docs.example.com/llms.txt</code>,
            <code>blog.example.com/llms.txt</code>. Each subdomain can have its own llms.txt.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What about non-English sites?</h3>
          <p>
            Write your llms.txt in whatever language your site is in. AI models are multilingual.
            If you serve content in multiple languages, you can include links to all language versions
            and note the language in the description.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="implementation">
        <h2>Implementation checklist</h2>
        <div class="checklist">
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Create <code>/llms.txt</code> at your domain root</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Add a title (<code># Site Name</code>) as the first line</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Add a description blockquote</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Organize links into sections (<code>## Docs</code>, <code>## Blog</code>, etc.)</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Use absolute URLs for all links</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Add colon-separated descriptions to each link</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Verify content type is <code>text/plain</code> or <code>text/markdown</code></label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Keep file size under 50KB</label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> Test with our <a href="/tools/playground">Playground validator</a></label>
          <label class="check-item"><input type="checkbox" /> <a href="/">Scan your domain</a> to verify your score</label>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <h3>Get started</h3>
        <p>Check your site's llms.txt or generate one from scratch.</p>
        <a href="/" class="action-btn action-btn-primary">Scan your domain</a>
        <a href="/tools/generator/llms-txt" class="action-btn action-btn-secondary">Generate llms.txt</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

